^-|cs||fp||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BLarry Cohen: ^*N|cp||at|I'll start with the very first thing on the ACBL convention card: NAMES. If you need help here, you might be in some trouble. Seriously, though, you should write both players' full names--your opponents are entitled to know.|
PG| ***** 7 ***** |


AT|

^*BOpening Bids and General System^*N
In my years of tournament success, I used Precision (discussed at the footnote at the end of this article) |CP|1|AT|^*Hwww.larryco.com/BridgeArticles/ArticleDetails.aspx?articleID=82^*N|CP||AT|. I suspect most readers will stick with what is familiar to them and play "Standard American."  "2-over-1 Game Forcing" is becoming more and more popular--and for good reason. "2/1" is a much easier system than "standard." I'd teach beginners that 1@S-2@C shows 13 and enough for game (as opposed to the 10 in the "book.")|
PG| ***** 8 ***** |


AT|

Eventually, I think, everyone will play 2/1 GF. (Of course, some of my inexperienced students can be found bidding 2-over-1 with 7 or 8 points--a definite no-no in any era with any system.) While a weak notrump (12-14) is popular in many countries, most of my readers prefer 15-17.|
PG| ***** 9 ***** |


AT|

Okay. So, for most of you the general approach will be "Standard"," or "2/1 GF", 15-17 notrump openings. Fine. What about the Strong Opening bid (2@C)?|
PG| ***** 10 ***** |


